1
0:0:24,326 --> 0:0:28,83
Two households,
both alike in dignity,


2
0:0:28,83 --> 0:0:35,336
in fair Verona
where we lay our scene,


3
0:0:35,336 --> 0:0:40,34
from ancient grudge
break to new mutiny,


4
0:0:40,34 --> 0:0:45,845
where civil blood
makes civil hands unclean.


5
0:0:45,845 --> 0:0:51,85
From forth the fatal loins
of these two foes...


6
0:0:51,85 --> 0:0:57,856
a pair of star-crossed lovers
take their life,


7
0:0:57,856 --> 0:1:3,294
whose misadventured
piteous overthrows


8
0:1:3,294 --> 0:1:29,317
do with their death...
bury their parents'strife.


9
0:1:29,317 --> 0:1:32,319
But the quarrel is between
our masters and us their men.


10
0:1:32,319 --> 0:1:36,323
Ah, 'tis all one.


11
0:1:36,323 --> 0:1:42,328
Here come the house
of the Montagues.


12
0:1:42,328 --> 0:1:43,829
Ah, good morrow.


13
0:1:43,829 --> 0:1:45,697
Good morrow
to you, sir.


14
0:1:45,697 --> 0:1:48,833
Quarrel,
I will back thee.


15
0:1:48,833 --> 0:1:50,335
Right.


16
0:1:50,335 --> 0:2:1,944
Fail me not.


17
0:2:1,944 --> 0:2:5,281
Do you bite
your thumb at us, sir?


18
0:2:5,281 --> 0:2:8,283
I do bite
my thumb, sir.


19
0:2:8,283 --> 0:2:13,288
Do you bite
your thumb at us, sir?


20
0:2:13,288 --> 0:2:15,79
No, sir.


21
0:2:15,79 --> 0:2:18,793
I do not bite my
thumb at you, sir,


22
0:2:18,793 --> 0:2:21,295
but I do bite
my thumb, sir.


23
0:2:21,295 --> 0:2:22,797
Do you quarrel, sir?


24
0:2:22,797 --> 0:2:28,301
Quarrel, sir?
No, no, no, sir.


25
0:2:28,301 --> 0:2:30,803
If you do, sir,
I am for you.


26
0:2:30,803 --> 0:2:32,805
I serve as good
a man as you.


27
0:2:32,805 --> 0:2:33,806
No better?


28
0:2:33,806 --> 0:2:39,31
Yes, better, sir.


29
0:2:39,31 --> 0:2:54,757
You lie.


30
0:2:54,757 --> 0:2:56,325
Draw!


31
0:2:56,325 --> 0:2:58,27
Draw if you be men!


32
0:2:58,27 --> 0:3:4,265
Gregory, remember
thy swashing blow!


33
0:3:4,265 --> 0:3:21,781
Kill the Capulets!


34
0:3:21,781 --> 0:3:24,283
Part, fools!
Put up your swords!


35
0:3:24,283 --> 0:3:26,284
You know not what you do!


36
0:3:26,284 --> 0:3:28,286
The Prince hath
expressly forbid


37
0:3:28,286 --> 0:3:30,388
this bandying
in Verona streets!


38
0:3:30,388 --> 0:3:34,291
Here come the Capulets!


39
0:3:34,291 --> 0:3:44,801
Tybalt, Capulet's kinsman!


40
0:3:44,801 --> 0:3:52,808
What, art thou drawn among
these heartless hinds?


41
0:3:52,808 --> 0:3:55,81
Turn thee, Benvolio.
Look upon thy death.


42
0:3:55,81 --> 0:3:57,311
I do but keep the peace.


43
0:3:57,311 --> 0:3:58,813
Put up thy sword


44
0:3:58,813 --> 0:4:1,249
or manage it
to part these men with me.


45
0:4:1,249 --> 0:4:4,5
What, drawn
and talk of peace?


46
0:4:4,5 --> 0:4:5,552
I hate the word,


47
0:4:5,552 --> 0:4:10,23
as I hate hell,
all Montagues and thee.


48
0:4:10,23 --> 0:4:11,59
Have at thee, cowards!


49
0:4:11,59 --> 0:4:13,392
Capulet!


50
0:4:13,392 --> 0:4:17,96
Montague!


51
0:4:17,96 --> 0:4:28,71
Capulet!


52
0:4:28,71 --> 0:4:30,4
Now hie thee home,
fragment.


53
0:4:30,4 --> 0:4:36,112
You villain!


54
0:4:36,112 --> 0:4:43,51
Capulet!


55
0:4:43,51 --> 0:4:46,388
Give me my long sword! Ho!


56
0:4:46,388 --> 0:4:47,789
Capulet!


57
0:4:47,789 --> 0:4:49,29
Down to the market square!


58
0:4:49,29 --> 0:4:51,292
Capulet!


59
0:4:51,292 --> 0:4:54,61
Follow me! Follow me!


60
0:4:54,61 --> 0:5:0,266
Kill that villain Montague!


61
0:5:0,266 --> 0:5:3,236
My noble uncle!
My noble uncle!


62
0:5:3,236 --> 0:5:5,37
What?


63
0:5:5,37 --> 0:5:8,24
My sword! My sword!


64
0:5:8,24 --> 0:5:12,243
Thou shalt not stir
a foot to seek a foe!


65
0:5:12,243 --> 0:5:16,147
Hold me not!
Let me go!


66
0:5:16,147 --> 0:5:18,249
Montague!


67
0:5:18,249 --> 0:5:19,749
Montague!


68
0:5:19,749 --> 0:5:46,39
Kill the villain!


69
0:5:46,39 --> 0:6:4,222
I'll strike thee, coward.


70
0:6:4,222 --> 0:6:5,923
The Prince!


71
0:6:5,923 --> 0:6:8,192
The Prince is coming!
Put down your weapons!


72
0:6:8,192 --> 0:6:10,494
The Prince!


73
0:6:10,494 --> 0:6:15,98
The Prince!


74
0:6:15,98 --> 0:6:17,367
Here comes the Prince!


75
0:6:17,367 --> 0:6:26,742
Put your weapons down!
The Prince!


76
0:6:26,742 --> 0:6:30,678
Rebellious subjects,
enemies to peace,


77
0:6:30,678 --> 0:6:33,247
throw your mistempered
weapons to the ground...


78
0:6:33,247 --> 0:6:36,516
Down with your weapons.


79
0:6:36,516 --> 0:6:44,757
And hear the sentence
of your moved Prince.


80
0:6:44,757 --> 0:6:49,261
Three civil brawls
bred of an airy word,


81
0:6:49,261 --> 0:6:50,829
by thee, old Capulet...


82
0:6:50,829 --> 0:6:56,0
No, no.


83
0:6:56,0 --> 0:6:58,403
And Montague...


84
0:6:58,403 --> 0:7:4,708
Have thrice disturbed
the quiet of our streets.


85
0:7:4,708 --> 0:7:8,21
If ever you disturb
our streets again,


86
0:7:8,21 --> 0:7:12,214
your lives shall pay
the forfeit of the peace.


87
0:7:12,214 --> 0:7:20,221
For this time
all the rest depart away!


88
0:7:20,221 --> 0:7:23,824
You, Capulet,
shall go along with me.


89
0:7:23,824 --> 0:7:29,229
And, Montague,
come you this afternoon.


90
0:7:29,229 --> 0:7:53,249
Once more, on pain of death,
all men depart.


91
0:7:53,249 --> 0:7:56,252
Where is Romeo?
Saw you him today?


92
0:7:56,252 --> 0:7:59,756
Right glad I am
he was not at this fray.


93
0:7:59,756 --> 0:8:2,191
Madam, an hour before
the worshipped sun


94
0:8:2,191 --> 0:8:4,76
peered forth
the golden window of the east,


95
0:8:4,76 --> 0:8:8,196
a troubled mind drove me
to walk abroad:


96
0:8:8,196 --> 0:8:10,698
where, underneath
the grove of sycamore


97
0:8:10,698 --> 0:8:12,867
so early walking
did I see your son.


98
0:8:12,867 --> 0:8:17,704
Towards him I made;
but he was ware of me,


99
0:8:17,704 --> 0:8:23,709
and stole into
the cover of the wood.


100
0:8:23,709 --> 0:8:32,55
Many a morning hath
he there been seen.


101
0:8:32,55 --> 0:8:42,392
See, where he comes.


102
0:8:42,392 --> 0:8:44,728
So please you, step aside.


103
0:8:44,728 --> 0:8:48,231
I'll know his grievance,
or be much denied.


104
0:8:48,231 --> 0:8:51,234
I would thou wert
so happy by thy stay,


105
0:8:51,234 --> 0:8:52,735
to hear true shrift.


106
0:8:52,735 --> 0:9:26,797
Come, madam. Let's away.


107
0:9:26,797 --> 0:9:34,204
Good morrow, cousin.


108
0:9:34,204 --> 0:9:36,39
Is the day so young?


109
0:9:36,39 --> 0:9:37,841
But new struck nine.


110
0:9:37,841 --> 0:9:41,21
Ay me!


111
0:9:41,21 --> 0:9:48,716
Sad hours seem long.


112
0:9:48,716 --> 0:9:52,72
Was that my father
that went hence so fast?


113
0:9:52,72 --> 0:10:1,562
It was.


114
0:10:1,562 --> 0:10:4,363
What sadness lengthens
Romeo's hours?


115
0:10:4,363 --> 0:10:14,539
Not having that, which having
makes them short.


116
0:10:14,539 --> 0:10:16,241
But, Romeo...


117
0:10:16,241 --> 0:10:29,752
Farewell, Coz.


118
0:10:29,752 --> 0:10:31,754
God's me,
what fray was here?


119
0:10:31,754 --> 0:10:33,255
Yet tell me not,


120
0:10:33,255 --> 0:10:37,759
for I have heard it all.


121
0:10:37,759 --> 0:10:43,764
Here's much to do with hate,
but more with love.


122
0:10:43,764 --> 0:10:52,672
Soft, I will go along.


123
0:10:52,672 --> 0:10:56,275
But Montague is bound
as well as l,


124
0:10:56,275 --> 0:10:59,278
in penalty alike,


125
0:10:59,278 --> 0:11:1,213
and 'tis not hard, I think,


126
0:11:1,213 --> 0:11:4,716
for men as old as we
to keep the peace.


127
0:11:4,716 --> 0:11:5,717
Oh...


128
0:11:5,717 --> 0:11:8,219
Of honorable reckoning
are you both,


129
0:11:8,219 --> 0:11:11,722
and pity 'tis you
lived at odds so long:


130
0:11:11,722 --> 0:11:15,726
but, but now, my lord,


131
0:11:15,726 --> 0:11:17,761
what say you to my suit?


132
0:11:17,761 --> 0:11:20,73
But saying o'er what
I have said before,


133
0:11:20,73 --> 0:11:24,934
my child is yet
a stranger in the world.


134
0:11:24,934 --> 0:11:34,75
She hath not seen the change
of fourteen years.


135
0:11:34,75 --> 0:11:37,244
Let two more summers
wither in their pride,


136
0:11:37,244 --> 0:11:39,179
'ere we may think her
ripe to be a bride.


137
0:11:39,179 --> 0:11:49,988
Younger than she
are happy mothers made.


138
0:11:49,988 --> 0:11:53,759
And too soon marred
are those so early made.


139
0:11:53,759 --> 0:11:56,762
The earth hath swallowed
all my hopes but she,


140
0:11:56,762 --> 0:11:59,764
she is the hopeful lady
of my earth.


141
0:11:59,764 --> 0:12:3,2
But woo her, gentle
Paris, get her heart,


142
0:12:3,2 --> 0:12:6,703
my will to her consent
is but a part.


143
0:12:6,703 --> 0:12:9,205
Oh, Peter!


144
0:12:9,205 --> 0:12:12,709
This night I hold
an old accustomed feast


145
0:12:12,709 --> 0:12:15,21
whereto I have invited
many a guest.


146
0:12:15,21 --> 0:12:18,213
Such as I love,
you among the store,


147
0:12:18,213 --> 0:12:29,222
one more, most welcome,
makes my number more.


148
0:12:29,222 --> 0:12:31,24
Nurse,
where's my daughter?


149
0:12:31,24 --> 0:12:33,226
Call her forth to me.


150
0:12:33,226 --> 0:12:35,228
Now, by my maidenhead
at 12 years old,


151
0:12:35,228 --> 0:12:36,796
I bade her come.


152
0:12:36,796 --> 0:12:40,199
Where is the girl?
Juliet! Juliet!


153
0:12:40,199 --> 0:12:44,436
Where is the girl?
Juliet!


154
0:12:44,436 --> 0:12:48,74
Where is the girl? Juliet!


155
0:12:48,74 --> 0:12:51,241
How now, who calls?


156
0:12:51,241 --> 0:13:5,188
Your mother!
Your lady mother!


157
0:13:5,188 --> 0:13:8,19
Juliet, it's your mother,
your lady mother.


158
0:13:8,19 --> 0:13:10,192
Make haste, girl.
Make haste.


159
0:13:10,192 --> 0:13:14,195
Where were you?


160
0:13:14,195 --> 0:13:18,199
Madam, I am here.
What is your will?


161
0:13:18,199 --> 0:13:22,702
This is the matter.


162
0:13:22,702 --> 0:13:25,205
Make haste, girls.
Come on, come on.


163
0:13:25,205 --> 0:13:26,306
Nurse, um...


164
0:13:26,306 --> 0:13:36,715
give leave awhile,
we must talk in secret.


165
0:13:36,715 --> 0:13:39,717
Nurse, come back again.
I have remembered me.


166
0:13:39,717 --> 0:13:43,221
Thou's hear our counsel.


167
0:13:43,221 --> 0:13:45,222
Thou knowest my daughter's
of a pretty age.


168
0:13:45,222 --> 0:13:47,224
I can tell her age
unto an hour.


169
0:13:47,224 --> 0:13:48,715
She's not fourteen.


170
0:13:48,715 --> 0:13:50,617
I'll lay fourteen
of my teeth.


171
0:13:50,617 --> 0:13:52,618
And yet to
my teen be it spoke,


172
0:13:52,618 --> 0:13:54,62
I have but four,
she's not fourteen.


173
0:13:54,62 --> 0:13:56,322
How long is it
to Lammastide?


174
0:13:56,322 --> 0:13:58,123
A fortnight and odd days.


175
0:13:58,123 --> 0:14:0,558
Even or odd, of all
the days of the year,


176
0:14:0,558 --> 0:14:2,56
come Lammas Eve at night
shall she be fourteen.


177
0:14:2,56 --> 0:14:4,62
Susan and she--


178
0:14:4,62 --> 0:14:6,564
God rest all Christian
souls were of an age.


179
0:14:6,564 --> 0:14:9,66
Well, Susan is with God.
She was too good for me.


180
0:14:9,66 --> 0:14:10,934
But, as I said,
on Lammas Eve


181
0:14:10,934 --> 0:14:13,103
at night
shall she be fourteen.


182
0:14:13,103 --> 0:14:15,372
That shall she, marry!
I remember it well.


183
0:14:15,372 --> 0:14:19,75
My lord and you
were then at Mantua!


184
0:14:19,75 --> 0:14:21,577
Nay, I do bear a brain.


185
0:14:21,577 --> 0:14:24,79
For then she could,
she could stand high lone.


186
0:14:24,79 --> 0:14:27,82
Nay, by the road she could have
run and waddled all about,


187
0:14:27,82 --> 0:14:30,85
for even the day before
she broke her brow;


188
0:14:30,85 --> 0:14:34,54
and then my husband-- God rest his soul,
'a were a merry man--


189
0:14:34,54 --> 0:14:35,556
took up the child.


190
0:14:35,556 --> 0:14:39,92
"Yea," quoth he,
"dost thou fall upon thy face?


191
0:14:39,92 --> 0:14:42,28
"Thou wilt fall backward
when thou hast more wit;


192
0:14:42,28 --> 0:14:43,96
wilt thou not, Jule?"


193
0:14:43,96 --> 0:14:45,98
Nurse!


194
0:14:45,98 --> 0:14:46,598
And by my holiday,


195
0:14:46,598 --> 0:14:53,105
the pretty wretch left
crying and said, "Ay."


196
0:14:53,105 --> 0:14:56,107
Enough of this,
I pray thee hold thy peace.


197
0:14:56,107 --> 0:14:58,709
Yes, madam.


198
0:14:58,709 --> 0:15:4,47
Now, Juliet.


199
0:15:4,47 --> 0:15:6,549
God mark thee to His grace


200
0:15:6,549 --> 0:15:9,985
Thou was the prettiest babe
that 'er I nurs'd.


201
0:15:9,985 --> 0:15:12,54
And I might live to see
thee married once,


202
0:15:12,54 --> 0:15:13,989
I have my wish.


203
0:15:13,989 --> 0:15:20,561
Marry, that "marry" is the very theme
I came to talk of.


204
0:15:20,561 --> 0:15:21,829
Tell me,
daughter Juliet,


205
0:15:21,829 --> 0:15:32,571
how stands your disposition
to be married?


206
0:15:32,571 --> 0:15:35,74
It is an honor
that I dream not of.


207
0:15:35,74 --> 0:15:37,576
An honor, were I not
thy only nurse,


208
0:15:37,576 --> 0:15:40,545
I would say thou hadst sucked
wisdom from my teat.


209
0:15:40,545 --> 0:15:43,81
Well, think
of marriage now.


210
0:15:43,81 --> 0:15:46,84
Younger than you, here in Verona,
ladies of esteem,


211
0:15:46,84 --> 0:15:47,584
are made
already mothers.


212
0:15:47,584 --> 0:15:50,87
By my count
I was your mother


213
0:15:50,87 --> 0:15:53,9
much upon these years
that you are now a maid.


214
0:15:53,9 --> 0:15:54,591
Oh, yes, I remember.


215
0:15:54,591 --> 0:15:57,427
Thus then, in brief...


216
0:15:57,427 --> 0:16:0,363
the valiant Paris
seeks you for his love.


217
0:16:0,363 --> 0:16:5,534
A man, young lady!
Lady, such as all the world--


218
0:16:5,534 --> 0:16:7,536
Why he's a man of wax.


219
0:16:7,536 --> 0:16:9,538
Verona's summer hath
not such a flower.


220
0:16:9,538 --> 0:16:11,539
Nay, he's
a flower in faith.


221
0:16:11,539 --> 0:16:13,4
Shh.


222
0:16:13,4 --> 0:16:19,546
What say you?
Can you love the gentleman?


223
0:16:19,546 --> 0:16:21,381
Madam! Madam!


224
0:16:21,381 --> 0:16:23,55
The guests have come,
supper serv'd up,


225
0:16:23,55 --> 0:16:25,751
you call'd,
my young lady ask'd for!


226
0:16:25,751 --> 0:16:28,53
We follow.


227
0:16:28,53 --> 0:16:32,57
Speak briefly,
can you like of Paris' love?


228
0:16:32,57 --> 0:16:37,562
I'll look to like,
if looking liking move.


229
0:16:37,562 --> 0:16:41,64
But no more deep
will I endart mine eye,


230
0:16:41,64 --> 0:16:47,571
than your consent gives
strength to make it fly.


231
0:16:47,571 --> 0:16:50,573
Juliet, the county stays.


232
0:16:50,573 --> 0:16:53,576
Madam, I come.


233
0:16:53,576 --> 0:17:20,765
Go, girl, seek happy nights
for happy days.


234
0:17:20,765 --> 0:17:24,269
Give me a case
to put my visage in;


235
0:17:24,269 --> 0:17:26,304
a visor for a visor.


236
0:17:26,304 --> 0:17:31,41
What care I what curious eye
doth quote deformities.


237
0:17:31,41 --> 0:17:38,381
Here are the beetle-brows
shall blush for me.


238
0:17:38,381 --> 0:17:40,55
What, shall this speech
be spoke for our excuse?


239
0:17:40,55 --> 0:17:42,551
Or shall we on
without apology?


240
0:17:42,551 --> 0:17:44,386
The date is out
of such prolixity.


241
0:17:44,386 --> 0:17:46,321
Let them measure us
by what they will.


242
0:17:46,321 --> 0:17:48,557
We'll measure them
a measure and be gone.


243
0:17:48,557 --> 0:17:51,559
Come, knock and enter,
and no sooner in,


244
0:17:51,559 --> 0:17:55,429
but every man
betake him to his legs.


245
0:17:55,429 --> 0:17:58,64
And we mean well in
going to this masque,


246
0:17:58,64 --> 0:17:59,533
but 'tis no wit to go.


247
0:17:59,533 --> 0:18:1,301
Why, may one ask?


248
0:18:1,301 --> 0:18:5,471
I dreamt a dream tonight.


249
0:18:5,471 --> 0:18:7,306
Ho, and so did I.


250
0:18:7,306 --> 0:18:10,876
Well, what was yours?


251
0:18:10,876 --> 0:18:14,279
That dreamers often lie.


252
0:18:14,279 --> 0:18:18,95
In bed asleep while they
do dream things true.


253
0:18:18,95 --> 0:18:22,586
Oh, then I see Queen Mab
hath been with you.


254
0:18:22,586 --> 0:18:25,322
Queen Mab?


255
0:18:25,322 --> 0:18:32,528
She is...She is
the fairies' midwife.


256
0:18:32,528 --> 0:18:33,963
And she comes in state


257
0:18:33,963 --> 0:18:36,464
no bigger than
an agate stone


258
